recordings.loc: Shark Valley, Everglades National Park, Miami-Dade County, Florida
recordings.rmk: Lifer; many birds seen along the canal, very vocal. Two birds here near the entrance.

A second Anhinga called from a distance and the Anhinga in front of me responded with this call. The Anhinga was on a small bare tree growing in the water. There were many other birds in the area, including many Boat-tailed Grackles, several species of warblers, some Blue-Gray Gnatcatchers, a Loggerhead Shrike, White Ibis, and Common Gallinules. The Anhinga had its wings folded (it was not drying them).

Approximately 30 American Coots and several Common Gallinules were swimming in shallow water in this direction, with an Anhinga perched on a branch.  Lots of herbaceous plants growing in and near the shores of the lake, and Spanish moss-draped trees on the distant shore.  Alligators were in the lake, and a Bald Eagle flew over the coots, scaring them, a short time after this recording was made.  100s of Coots were on the other side of the dike I was walking on.
The Anhinga called twice on the recording, the second time a couple of seconds before the end.
